The tenant of Bakal: The stoves are heating, he has signed a higher rent.
An imposing old man came out the door of the customer center of the RPG company Byty of the "coal baron" Zdenek Bakal, the largest private owner of apartments for rent in the Czech Republic.
He had a file under his arm with three new leases for three apartments: his own, his daughter’s and his son’s, who is about to serve a sentence.
Deregulation has led to an increase in rent for these three people.
Instead of paying 3500 the son will have to pay from next year for a 2+1 apartment of the second category 4100 crowns.
“And there’s no hot water and the heating works on solid fuel,” points to her son’s new contract with the man who has the power to sign.
"But I signed anyway," he explains in anger and half resigned.
The citizen association of apartments BytyOKD.cz, which described the new rental conditions as "immoral and indecent", advises tenants not to sign and wait until December 7, when a notice will be published to explain the method to be followed to claim.
But the man reacts to this with a gesture of his hand.
"One says that, the other says something else," frowning.
The Ostrava region becomes the laboratory of deregulation.
After the New Year, this is what awaits most apartments in the Czech Republic whose rents do not correspond to the market price.
Aktualne.cz has therefore decided to personally visit the "laboratory".
The RPG waiting room in Havirovska Street is one of the four in the Ostrava region and is already full on Tuesday at 9 a.m.
Just next to the door stands a guard of a security company with a device to call customers.
A special button, "rent 2011", is lit on the touch screen.
A single press and a paper with a number comes out of the device.
You do not have time to read your number "157" as your number already begins to light up on the big screen under the top of the waiting room.
In a fraction of a second, it's your turn.
After a short moment, an old couple arrives to inquire about the rent, but the new rents do not seem to concern the people in the waiting room.
The majority of people have come to solve common problems as everywhere - requests for repairs, insurance events and others.
In the Ostrava region, people from more than 44,000 apartments in the RPG portfolio have been receiving mail with the new leases in their mailbox since about mid-November.
RPG Byty offers them rent increases of 15 to 38 percent.
The special window for new rentals has been open to the public since November 18.
"it's been working for almost a week, so it's still on trial," replies the employee behind the counter after a moment of hesitation when the client presents himself as a journalist.
Deragulation and the former Bakal miners' apartments are a very sensitive local topic.
The Vice-President of the Parliament and from the region of Ostrava Lubomir Zaoralek of the Social Democrats reported this in a rather supportive way before the elections and it now fills the local newspapers.
“Twenty years later, I want a new floor.”
"They didn't even change a board put...n in the toilets, relieved in the introduction the man mentioned.
However, it is mostly, according to employees, retirees who come to be sure that they will receive a discount on the new rent price if they sign now as promised by RPG in a special offer.
This is a reduction of half of the rent that will be received by the other tenants who will have signed their new contract before December 15.
But the "deregulation" window of Havirovaska Street is really not overwhelmed by the issues.
"Of the 360 customers who came yesterday, only 40 to 50 came for the rent," the employee said at the counter.
And yet RPG porpose both on its website and in the showcases of individual interviews on rents when necessary.
If the two parties do not agree on the rent, the decision will be taken by an independent court.
“It’s not about threats, it’s just about informing about the unique and legitimate way to act legally,” says RPG on its website.
"No one's going to court here," one of Byty's RPG employees thinks, and the man in the street in front of the customer center gives her reason.
“I have 13,000 crowns of retirement and I have 5,000 crowns left to eat, I don’t have enough to go to court,” he says.
The employee suddenly feels uneasy.
"We'll see."
"Mr. Zaoralek in the media asks that no one sign and so people are waiting," she said.
Rent regulation ends in the Czech Republic with the beginning of 2011 and increases, according to RPG Byty, are an economic necessity.
"And, in addition, the current rents still do not reach the level necessary for the simple maintenance of the fund for housing," recalls Pavel Klimes, director of the residential portfolio of the company RPG Byty, that it is the neglect of the fund for housing that makes the tenant angry is the main reason for the increase in rent.
However, in 5 years between 2005 and 2010 RPG was able to invest with rents in apartments 4 billion, in four years from 2011 to 2014 it is expected to make 5.2 billion.
The large screen hanging from the ceiling in front of the upholstered armchairs of the waiting room on Havirosvka Street, however, repeats some information indicated in red.
The increase in rent in 2011 is 15 percent and concerns no less than 31,200 apartments, or more than 90 percent of RPG apartments.
"And it will always be a maximum of 7.50 Czech crowns per m2 per month," says the screen.
The 38 percent increase concerns only 400 apartments in the RPG portfolio.
"In these cases, this is an increase of a really very low amount of 19.66 Czech crowns per m2," adds RPG.
Next year the rent will remain the same for 2600 apartments.
RPG Byty promises that deregulation will not cause a radical but gradual increase over 4 to 8 years.
It adds other commitments: all the money from the rent increase (see graph) is returned to the apartments in the form of heating savings - new windows and heating.
Those who sign the agreement on the rent increase have priority.
The kindergarten is part of, too, offices have understood the architects.
the administrative building Avriopoint Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch. Design.
