The house in bone still fascinates after 100 years. Take a look at the interiors of Gaudi.
The roof resembles the back of a prehistoric saurian, the staircase to a dinosaur spine and the balconies to open fish mouths.
This is how the Casa Battlo house in Barcelona of the architect Antoni Gaudi is.
Due to its organic forms, the house received the nickname of Bone House from the locals.
Organic forms, wild colors, unusual use of stones, fragments of tiles and mosaic, facade reminiscent of scales and everywhere present curves, this is all that is typical of Art Nouveau by Antoni Gaudi.
The front facade of the house unfolds its dream lines, its colors and pleasant textures that remind nature and animals.
In the course of a more detailed observation, we see geometry, rhythm and precisely thought-out order.
At night the facade of the house becomes even more dramatic and is lit in such a way that the impression of brightness of the colors is reinforced by it.
The winding and twisting of the shapes also appears in the interiors with the same measurement.
The wood copied in waves the window frames, railings, decorative elements of the doors, the eyelet and the slats.
The house Battlo which stands in the Eixample district in the shopping street Passeig de Gracia at number 43, was born from the construction of a house from 1877 by the architect Emilio Sala Cortes.
Reconstruction took place for two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, Joseph Battlo, a wealthy entrepreneur, first insisted on demolishing the old building and building another brand new one but quickly accepted Gaudi's idea of an unusual and cheaper reconstruction.
But the idea of Casa Battlo as a multi-family house was not conceived by Gaudi alone.
The architect Josep Maria Jujol worked with him.
It was on his project that the decorations for an apartment of representation of the owner of the building and the use of the mosaic for the facade were born.
For the fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade also worked other artists and creators.
The joint work for the plans of Casa Battlo began with a successful cooperation between Jujol and Gaudi.
Jujol participated in the construction of Gaudi's Casa Mila house and Guell Park in which there are other works by Gaudi.
The locals nicknamed the hot house just after it was finished because of its organic shapes "the House in Bone".
Others, given the specific mechanism of opening the windows, called it "the house that rents".
It is said that at the top of the construction there is a sword similar to that of Saint George the patron of Catalonia.
Other elements of the construction sculpture contain hidden religious motifs.
Gaudi thought for the house a unique system in its central heating time, with ventilation vents and typical fireplaces.
Their inclination of 45 degrees seems strange.
During the creation, Gaudi absolutely did not follow the construction guidelines of the time and did not allow himself to be hindered by them.
At the beginning of the construction he obtained from the city the building permit, knowing, of course, that the data carried on the reconstruction plans were so vague that two years later during the completion the city council was horrified and asked for changes.
The members of the city council, for example, did not like the pillars of construction being pushed onto the public sidewalk.
There was never any change, but, on the contrary, only 15 days after the call of the city Josep Battlo asked (and got satisfaction) permission to rent the two highest floors.
The owner moved to the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor there was a common living room and on the third a bedroom and a private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewellery store.
The entire six-storey house is shared by a staircase through which one accesses to an independent roof terrace.
All right angles and straight lines were annulled by the basic elements of the reconstruction and replaced by curved walls.
Gaudi also worked on the modern concept of connecting spaces.
The communal part can be fully connected by opening the doors of the salons and the high society can communicate comfortably or limit the private space for more intimate interviews.
The house with the reconstruction of Gaudi received a non-traditional roof and two additional floors.
Gaudi’s play with light is also impressive, with blue and white glass tiles with which the inner courtyard is decorated and with the wells of light.
The two-color game gives maximum light in all floors of the house.
It was enough just to bet on the principle that white reflects more than dark, which on the contrary absorbs the rays of the sun.
The Casa Battlo house that was inscribed in 2005 in the UNESCO World Heritage Fund may be visited by everyone.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and splendid apartment accessible to the public.
The owners decided to take this step in 2002 on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
They continued the visits because they found it to be a lucrative business and they expanded the scope of visits to common areas and attic including roof terraces.
The entrance ticket to the monument is really cheap and costs 16.50 euros; students, retirees, groups and holders of tourist cards have 20 percent discount.
The sum is still above the entrance price to the other constructions of Gaudi in the city.
If you want to feel the real atmosphere of the house with its fantastic turrets, you need to quickly find a comrade among the residents of the building and visit the house completely.
