Devices to track people are increasingly in demand by parents who want to monitor their children.
Fear for their child leads more and more people to think about monitoring them through a GPS.
The system, set up at the beginning to search for cars, can just as well be used to track the movement of people and help in some cases as for example that of little Anicka Janatkova.
The instrument is currently as large as a matchbox but will soon be the size of a watch.
The case of little Anicka moved a large number of people and they began to look for ways to better protect their children.
Even if the price is to disturb their privacy.
"We are trying to tell everyone that this is not spying but just another way to reduce the likelihood of another tragedy," said Petr Pilin of the company MACRO Weil, which is one of the suppliers of tracking devices in the Czech market.
"I admit that there may be cases of misuse of such devices, such as putting it in the bag of a person who is not aware, but I have not yet encountered such cases."
“The majority of people are customers who actually buy the product for safety reasons,” Pilin adds.
According to him, children should always know for what purposes "the box" is used and how to use it in an emergency.
The child psychologist, Dana Bockova, draws attention to the fact that if the child does not want to wear such a thing on him, he will get rid of it.
“And even the little ones can show great creativity when it comes to deliberately getting rid of something when they don’t want to be under control.”
“Mobile phones, which can cut themselves like these tracking devices, have already led parents to long expectations,” says Bockova.
According to her, the fact that this type of device can help in case of aggression is very questionable.
"If this is a prepared kidnapping, the author will do everything so that the child does not have an electronic device that can locate him."
“Currently, it’s the phone.”
"As soon as the tracking devices are going to develop, they (the criminals) will be looking for them too because the sale will be supported by an advertising campaign."
“In such cases, criminals will always be ahead of the police,” says the psychologist.
She still admits that such devices can help during an unprepared aggression by a pedophile.
According to Robert Cech of the company RC Monitoring, which offers tracking services for both cars and people, says that having this type of device can help, even if it is destroyed in the event of an assault.
"The apparatus may be set up in such a way that it is in regular broadcast after a specified period of time."
"In the event that the device is destroyed, it still remains the last position of the person concerned."
"The more expensive devices also have an inclinometer that immediately signals the position of the person who has slipped and is in the elongated position without moving," says Cech.
According to him, so-called smart phones that are equipped with a navigation system, can offer a comparable service after having formatted it with a special protocol.
The problem with current tracking systems is that it is either a device similar to those worn in pendants the size of a litter box or to the smallest telephone devices.
We can always lose them.
According to Pilina of the company Macro Weil, this is why tests are currently being conducted to make devices that look like common digital watches.
"This will have the advantage that the potential aggressor will not be able to recognize the tracking device."
"Or he will realize it after a while, which will have given the police a little more time," he added.
Whether the tracking device is developed in the form of a bracelet or pendant, it will always use the same technology as for tracking cars.
It is a combination of GPS position acquisition systems (which is commonly used in self-navigation) and a mobile phone function that alerts the current position of a vehicle.
