In the building of the Land Fund in Plzen, the anti-corruption police have made arrests in recent days.
The detectives handed over the handcuffs to the local contractor and real estate merchant Lubos.
The latter had endeavoured to manipulate a public call for tenders for the settlement of a return application in such a way that the proposed land would be obtained by a particular candidate.
He had to pay Lubos G. half a million crowns.
"At the moment, I can only confirm that the police are prosecuting a person for insider's misconduct as part of a public tender and competition," Plzen prosecutor Antonie Zelena told the Pravo newspaper, knowing that it is forbidden to provide further explanations as the investigation is ongoing.
Police released the 46-year-old contractor after 24 hours.
To find out how it could influence a public competition, one can only speculate in light of so little official information.
On a question from Pravo, Lubomira Cerna, a spokeswoman for the Land Fund, said the police had actually been arrested in Plzen at a separate workplace during the public contest.
"It was a customer and in no case an employee," she said.
The public competition according to Cerna has the real name "Call to propose rights for the transfer of land according to the Land Act" and is set up when several eligible candidates appear.
"These persons propose, in the context of the appeal, a higher value of their restitution rights that must be settled before the value of the land is announced."
“According to the proposed rights, a ranking of the acquirers is set up and the Land Fund then transfers the land to the person who proposed the highest rights,” the fund’s spokesman said.
Lubos G. had, it is clear, information about the persons who had registered for the appeal and, as he is himself, also a person bévilare because having purchased a large number of refund rights, he had proposed to candidates in the field not to participate in the competition.
