Households will pay an additional one hundred crowns per month for housing.
Starting in January, households will have to pay a supplement not only for all types of energy but also for water and sanitation, heating supplies and in some places rents will also increase.
As of January, families will have to draw up to a hundred crowns a month more from their wallets than now.
Electricity increases by 4.6 percent, gas by almost 2 percent more expensive, in some localities you will have to pay up to a tenth more for water supply and in many places central heating supplies will also be more expensive.
The increase in electricity is expected to be close to 100 crowns per annum for households in apartments than currently.
However, all suppliers have lowered electricity prices due to the sensitive development to encourage the production of renewable energies, including photovoltaic batteries.
Gas increases moderately but of course at the time when people need it most to heat and thus have the highest consumption.
One can also count a hundred crowns in addition.
Although electricity and gas are increasing throughout the Czech Republic, the change in the price of central heating differs from city to city.
It is mainly the largest municipalities that plan to increase prices.
For example, households in Pardubice or Hradec Kraloce will pay almost 50 crowns more per month from January onwards, while families in Liberec will pay more than 1000 crowns per year.
For residents of Prague is preparing a 9 percent increase in water and sanitation in case the city increases infrastructure rents.
If the rents do not change the thresholds will pay an additional 6.8 percent.
The price in Prague will still be among the lowest in comparison with the whole country.
In northern Bohemia, where prices are already among the highest, water and sanitation are up 7.4 percent.
For example, rent prices will rise significantly in the 450,000 apartments rented from January, i.e. at the end of the regulation.
For example, the company CPI Byty, which owns almost 2500 apartments in Usti nad Labem, decided to increase it to 100 percent.
Those who will not agree with the new rent increase will be brought before the courts by the company.
Regulated rents paid by people in nearly 300,000 apartments could increase by 10 percent next year.
Czech children get drunk with rum and fernet. Beer is no longer fashionable and acts all gently.
Fernet, rum, vodka and exceptionally also the best brand of whisky are stolen from parents.
These are drinks that most often bring those who are drunk, who are not yet fifteen years old, into the hands of the doctor.
Children who are treated in the hospital for recurrence are no exception.
This is a result of the experience of doctors who encounter cases similar to admissions from hospital children's departments.
“Beers or wines are no longer fashionable because it takes time to get drunk.”
'The trend is really to strong alcohols,' says Pravo Ludek Pelikan, Head of Children's Department at Horovice Hospital in Central Bohemia.
“When they manage to chip a bottle in the closet, it’s sometimes whiskey, but it’s the fernet and vodka that prevail.”
"Wodka has the advantage that they can mix it with fruit juice and thus not feel it," explains the head of the department.
Eva Jurinova, a spokeswoman for the Motol Hospital, also gives her reason.
"In general, it's rum or fernet."
"It's today fashionable alcohol, especially in elementary schools."
"In some cases, it was slivovice that they brought back from the house," Jurinova added.
According to the head of the Pelikan department, seeing drunken children between the ages of thirteen and fourteen at hospital admissions is a normal phenomenon.
Before working in Horovice since last year, he was in Motol where he spent ten years in paediatrics, where ambulances brought completely drunk schoolchildren from the wide area.
"A young girl was hospitalized four times.
"She began her career at the age of twelve when she was brought in with 3.5 per thousand alcohol in the blood with in addition a mixture with ecstasy," the doctor described this particularly important case.
"She was at the Holesovice Exhibition Park at a party."
"What's interesting is that it didn't seem strange to the mother that her daughter was absent for 48 hours," said the director of the department.
It is precisely the disinterest of the parents or their extraordinary tolerance for the fact that their rejections are given to the drink that is the main cause of the development of alcoholism of children.
According to experts, however, we do not talk about dependence, in its strict sense, for children.
“Under the term alcohol we mean a chronic alcohol dependence of several years with all the phenomena that result from it but that we do not find in children.”
"In those who use repetitive alcohol, it is rather a significantly unfavorable socio-family background," explained the head of the Pelikan Department.
According to spokeswoman Jurinova, about forty drunken children were hospitalized this year until mid-November in the pediatric clinic in Motol.
Only cases with severe intoxication requiring hospitalization are included in the statistics.
Drunk children who are brought home after emergency care by their parents or by the police are not counted.
In addition to the cases of children sitting and drinking a bottle of alcohol after school, according to Pelikan, there are three seasonal waves with which one can count: the day of the witches, Saint Sylvester and the end of the school year.
"Either they drink despite bad results or on the contrary they celebrate the beginning of the holidays."
"Of course I experienced on witches' day an admission of seven drunken children at a time," Pelikan said.
The drunken child who spent the night in the hospital in detoxification under medical supervision is paradoxically in a better position than the one who returned home and suffers the next day from the "mouth of wood".
Morning headaches caused by dehydration and lack of glucose are eliminated by an infusion of glucose and nutrients that the body needs.
“They’re better off because they spend a great evening and then a sweet awakening and nothing hurts them.”
“They’re just amazed at where they are,” Pelikan adds, knowing that from time to time it spoils the good mood of patients at least with the note to pay for their care.
Ambulance transport and hospitalization on intensive care beds can cost up to tens of thousands of crowns.
"From time to time, I applied this as a means of education by telling these children how much their intoxication cost and that they could spend the whole summer in seasonal work to pay off a single evening," Pelikan added.
However, according to him, health insurance companies in their regressive management, which are expected to recover care-related burdens from parents, do not treat cases of drunken children.
Two L-159 aircraft are in foreign hands in Spain for the first time.
Two of the five L-159s, against which the Ministry of Defense exchanged Casa C-295M transport aircraft, took off Tuesday for Seville, Spain, where aircraft manufacturer Casa-EADS is based.
This is the first time that such devices have become the property of someone other than the Czech army.
However, they have been abroad in the course of exercises or demonstration flights.
These are the two-seat versions of the L-159T1 that were previously in service in the Czech Army and were in flight.
The remaining three aircraft are single-seat versions of the L-159.
These are currently parked at Aero Vodochody and the commercial intermediary - the firm Omnipol - took them into account last week.
According to Jan Pejsek of the press department of the Ministry of Defense, the physical departure of the Vodochody aircraft is currently unknown.
"The L-159 single-seater aircraft planned for the exchange were taken from long-stocked aircraft without causing any additional charges or investments for the Ministry of Defence."
"The L-159 T1 two-seaters have been exchanged in the state," Pravo Pejsek said.
He joked that the army will not be without two seats since the ministry signed in May 2009 with Aero Vodochody an agreement worth 200 million crowns for the transformation of four unused L-159 single-seaters into two two-seaters.
The army took delivery of the first aircraft in July, with the second scheduled for delivery later this year.
According to Pejsek, EADS is committed to introducing the aircraft into the equipment of some Alliance countries.
“The contract clearly states that the one who takes the L-159s into account is EADS and that they will be used for training pilots from NATO member countries.”
"It is therefore the case of the one who is considering how to achieve this," Pejsek said.
Hospodarske noviny announced, some time ago, that the Spanish army is not interested in the L-159.
The exchange of five L-159s for a Casa aircraft and the purchase of three other aircraft for 3.5 billion crowns was approved last year by the government of Mirek Topomanek.
The Department of Defense did not issue a call for tenders and contacted EADS directly.
The Defense Department then argued that the exchange ensures a future export of the L-159 abroad.
The Czech army bought 72 aircraft from Aero Vodochody and only uses 24, wanting to sell the rest.
The purchase of Casa aircraft is likely to have legal implications.
The European Commission, however, filed a complaint against the Czech Ministry of Defence with the European Court of Justice because the aircraft should have been selected as part of a European-wide call for tenders and in no case by contacting a manufacturer directly.
The army has already taken delivery of three Casa planes, the last one is expected to arrive at Prague Kbely airport in two weeks.
An index longer than the annular is a sign of low risk of cancer
Men who have the index longer than the annular are at a lower risk of having prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published Wednesday by the British magazine Cancer.
This may depend on the level of the male hormone testosterone.
"Our findings show that relative finger length serves as a simple test for prostate cancer risk, particularly for men before age 60," said study co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at Warwick University.
The finger could help determine which men should be tested for prostate cancer, including by combining it with genetic risk or other aggravating factors such as family health history, Eeles added.
During the period 1994-2009 she followed with her colleagues in Britain more than 1500 patients with prostate cancer and at the same time nearly three thousand healthy men.
More than half of the study participants had the index of the right hand shorter than the annular.
For them as for the 19 percent of those who had fingers of the same length, the same probability of prostate cancer was found.
In the case of those who had the index longer than the annular risk, however, fell to 33 percent, for men before the age of 60 the decrease in risk reached 87 percent.
The length ratio of the two fingers cited - formed during the prenatal period - indicates in particular different levels of sex hormones to which the child is exposed in the uterus.
Less testosterone corresponds to a longer index.
Previous research had shown that it is precisely testosterone that helps in the development of prostate cancer.
Professor Vacla Paces, a renowned Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, told CTK that he is aware of the study but does not believe that the relationship between finger length and cancer is "fully demonstrated".
