Some 44% of respondents in the region said they were satisfied with the way their country's democracy worked in practice; this was the same as last year but with a sharp increase from 25% in 2001 (Figure 3)
Some 34 per cent said they had confidence in their country's parliament and 45 per cent in their government, the same as last year in both cases; but a sharp increase compared to 2003 (17 per cent and 24 per cent, respectively).
Ten years ago, economic problems in Latin America rocked support for democracy.
While this has been good during the global financial crisis, it is certainly due to the fact that many countries in America have experienced only a brief recession and have benefited from a strong recovery.
In addition, a social security network has helped protect the poor.
(The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America reported this week that the proportion of Latin Americans living in poverty increased only slightly in 2009 and fell again this year to 32%.)
But the mood varies considerably from country to country (see Chart 4).
Brazil’s good economic performance and the popularity of its outgoing president, Luiz In<0xC3><0xA1>cio Lula da Silva, translates into a widely shared sense of progress
This is rarer in Mexico and Central America where the recession has been more severe and violent crimes have aggravated.
This is only the second time since the survey began that more respondents across Latin America as a whole have cited crime rather than unemployment as the most important problem for their country (see Table 5).
About 31 per cent say they or one of their loved ones have been the victim of a criminal act in the past year; however, this figure is down from 38 per cent last year and is the lowest since 1995.
More robust economic performance is reflected in increased support for private enterprise and the market economy: about 71% of respondents in the region say private enterprise is indispensable for development, compared with 56% in 2007 (see Chart 6).
Some 58% believe that the market economy is the only system that will make their country developed, compared to 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62% of respondents in Venezuela are of this opinion (and 80% support private enterprise); although their left-wing president, Hugo Chavez, expropriates many private companies.
Brazil is the largest leader in the region, mentioned by 19% of respondents (compared to 18% last year), followed by the United States (9%, unchanged from last year) and Venezuela (9%, down 11% from last year).
But the United States is considered the most influential country by respondents in Mexico and most of Central America, while Venezuela enjoys this distinction in Ecuador, the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
A dirty vote
No one expected a perfect general election in Haiti on November 28.
But it was far worse than the outsiders who wanted to help the country ravaged and plunged into fear.
Voting boxes and re-election were presented, ballot papers scattered in the gutters, sacked polling stations and intimidation
The polling stations opened late in the evening.
Many Haitians, including many who were displaced following the January earthquake, wandered around the neighborhood to find where to vote.
Some of them ended up giving up.
A dozen presidential candidates, including several alleged favorites, denounced the fraud and called for the cancellation of the election.
Protests, sometimes violent, have exploded across the country.
However, Edmond Mulet, the United Nations’ senior official in Haiti, considers the event to be “a pretty good election in many respects.”
Observers from the Organization of American States and the Caribbean Community cautiously stated that they "did not believe that these irregularities, however serious, necessarily invalidated the process."
In other words, the show continues.
The electoral authority, whose opponents are indebted to René Préval, the outgoing unpopular president, and his candidate, Jude Célestin, is due to announce the preliminary results on December 7.
The second round is scheduled for January.
All hope in the election is not lost.
The two opposition candidates, Michel Martelly, a rap musician, and Mirlande Manigat, a former first lady, withdrew from their initial call for the vote to be declared void.
But there may be problems if Mr. Célestin, who has little or no noticeable support among voters, is declared by the electoral authority as having reached the second round reached the second round.
With a cholera epidemic raging, and more than 1 million earthquake survivors still living in tents, there were fears of participation.
In this case, many Haitians wanted to vote but were prevented from voting because of the disorganization.
Nearly 250,000 identity cards needed to vote were not yet issued shortly before the election.
The stakes are important.
Donors see the election of a popular and legitimate government as an important step in Haiti’s reconstruction.
And so, it is clear, the Haitians do it themselves.
