In the weeks after she suddenly became a widow, Cristina Fern<0xC3><0xA1>ndez, President of Argentina, benefited from a wave of public sympathy that improved her approval rate from 20 points to more than 50%; this is her highest level since she was elected in 2007.
However, turning this into a successful campaign for a second term in an election next year could depend on Ms Fern<0xC3><0xA1>ndez’s choice, visibly in mourning, whether or not she would abandon the intransigence of her late husband, predecessor and former political partner, Néstor Kirchner.
And in this regard, the signs remain confused.
Kirchner, who continued to manage economic policy even after his wife succeeded him as president, was used to developing budgets that underestimated tax revenues, economic growth and inflation.
This allowed the first couple to spend the extra income at will.
Ms. Fern<0xC3><0xA1>ndez's government lost its majority in Congress last year, on paper.
But the opposition is divided, and the situation has plummeted in disarray following Mr. Kirchner's death from a heart attack on October 27.
Some of the dissident members of the Peronist movement in power joined with Ms. Fern<0xC3><0xA1>ndez.
But after chaotic sessions (where a parliamentarian slammed one of his peers in the face and others accused the government of corruption), Congress doesn’t have to approve the 2011 budget.
“I’m not going to argue,” the president said.
