Although the department judge refused to explain the reasoning that led to the decision in the Ensign case, Mr. Brand and other ethics lawyers said that the department appeared to be wary of political prosecutions after a number of high-level setbacks cashed in by its public integrity section.
Federal prosecutors are clearly afraid to take up arms, said Melanie Sloan, the general director of citizens for accountability and ethics in Washington, a defense group that has received several complaints against Mr. Ensign in the case.
"This basically says high-ranking government officials can now assume the laws don't apply to them," she added.
