Zapatero and the German Red Line
Berlin has chosen to remain in the euro, but it has set the conditions for the whole Union.
Market tensions have prompted a double government response.
On the one hand, José Luis Rodr<0xC3><0xAD>guez Zapatero announced new adjustment methods, which range from tax reductions for SMEs, regulation of private investment agencies or the abolition of the 426 euros of unemployment aid without professional contribution to the privatization of the 49% state of AENA, of the management of the airports of Barajas and El Prat 30%
On the other hand, Vice-President Elena Salgado, with the support of former President Felipe Gonz<0xC3><0xA1>lez, joins the criticism of Chancellor Angela Merkel regarding her responsibility to detach the current crisis.
How should these movements be interpreted?
It should be mentioned that Merkel’s position is not a mistake in her communicative policy.
On the contrary, it is another restriction of the difficult process of redefining the euro.
And there Germany has a radically new vision of what its future should be, which clashes with that of maintaining the old traditions of most of its partners.
In the face of European resistance, Germany is beginning to speculate on the three possible exits from the crisis.
The first, a strong euro, integrated by itself, Austria and Holland, among other countries, and the south would abandon the monetary zone.
The second, the recovery of the Mark, although now it seems science fiction, with a very favorable current of opinion, almost 50% of the population.
The third is a redesign of the euro, in line with German proposals for greater macroeconomic control, budgetary rigour, fines for countries that transgress them, possible suspensions of payments of one of them and extension to the private sector of the costs of potential adjustments.
The German position is clear and it has long been defined, therefore now there is no room for excuses.
First, in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission were boosting deficits, the German government invented a constitutional reform to prevent them from 2016.
This was the first sign of divergence between what Germany thought we should do (tax rigor and fiscal stability plans) and what its European partners, including France, were practicing.
The second blow of the Central European country was when Merkel hardly prolonged the decision to save Greece.
From that moment on, it was fiercely criticized, but the truth is that the political consensus in Germany and public and public opinion were against Greece’s rescue.
Finally, towards the end of October, Merkel again expressed a clear position, calling for the reform of the EU treaties to make possible the rescue of a country and at the same time oblige private lenders to bear a share of the cost.
This position was interpreted as anti-European because it precipitated the Irish crisis and the rest.
But his proposal, although somewhat sweetened, was approved, and in the following months we should witness the Union's reform process that will make these measures possible from 2013 onwards.
Germany has drawn a red line that it does not think it will cross.
And it tells us all that, even if we now have to take measures with which we cannot agree too much, from that date the old functioning of the euro would have ended.
2013 will mark the birth of a new monetary zone, in which countries that break the rules will be severely sanctioned, they may be forced to declare cessation of payments and, in this case, the private sector will also bear a share of the costs.
Germany is signaling to us that we need to follow a strong growth path with high rates of savings and investment, moderation in consumption, improvements in productivity and competitiveness and positive external balances.
An alternative based on debt and construction, with huge gaps in the balance of payments, like the one that presided over Spanish growth in the boom years, will simply not be tolerated.
The bet is clear.
And it would be a shame not to hear it.
It is not just about bringing the government deficit back to 3% in 2013.
What we are asked for is much harder.
And what he absolutely should not do in these circumstances is to deceive ourselves.
I hope that the current turbulence will give us greater peace of mind.
And let us know how to seize the opportunity that we have been given, until the spring of 2013.
It seems that President Zapatero has also heard of this form and his double statement (the reforms promised after last Saturday's meeting with big companies and yesterday's announcement of new measures) suggests that, despite Merkel's criticism, the path has been paved for the thesis that order should be put at home.
But the red line that Germany has drawn is there, and they don’t seem to be moving it.
And among the possibilities that are being considered, one cannot exclude the possibility of leaving a monetary zone too full of small countries.
And in that case, Germany will always be able to tell us that it had warned us of it.
Sport and Fraud of the Law
The tricks similar to those of Alonso and Ramos against Ajax demonstrate ingenuity but not the will to escape a sanction.
The expulsion of two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) during the match on 23 November against Ajax in the Champions League has poured a lot of ink on the anti-sport character of such behavior and whether both players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As we know, a few minutes before the end of the game (which their team was already clearly winning), the two players deliberately lost time when they made mistakes in determining the referee to show them the second yellow card.
Thus, and since Real Madrid will end up being the leader of his group, the two players will complete the regulatory penalty during the next game of the dam match against Auxerre and will be able to pass without cards to the next phase.
Finally, the UEFA discipline committee sanctioned the team's coach, José Mourinho, and various economic sums to the players involved with two matches.
Provoking a yellow card in circumstances like this or similar is not a new practice, but rather common in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos, unwritten but followed rules, of this sport.
Part of the debate in the reported case is due to the fact that this had as protagonist a team of the entity of Real Madrid (which in its anthem displays the nobility and honor and who in past occasions has condemned to a fine to its players for similar acts) and to the dramatization provocateur, more of an orchestrated, it seems, by Mochur.
In any case, the debate asks whether this type of behaviour not expressly prohibited by the regulation contradicts the principles of sport, that is, whether these actions commit fraud; because, in fact, they are actions respectful of the sport regulation, but seem to evade its meaning.
The question is to examine the type of harm they cause to the sports mind.
One of the assets that understands the sporting spirit is the physical integrity of the opposing players, an aspect that with these actions has not been put in jeopardy, that is, there has been no violent play.
Another of these assets that is alluded to with correct play is to prevent the team of the offending players from unfairly profiting from the other team, which is not the case either.
However, the paradoxical fact of the action of Real Madrid players is that it does not accommodate what is normally characterized as cheating o fraud of the law, because its violation of the rules was not done in secret to try to avoid the penalty, but their action precisely tried to be as obvious as possible to receive the penalty.
They waited and gladly accepted the penalty.
Another issue is the type of benefit that offenders receive from the intentional mistakes examined.
Here it seems necessary to find that one does not put the opponent at a disadvantage and one does not get an advantage in the same match either, because obviously the result of the action implies leaving their own team with fewer players.
And it's not a useful strategy for the next game either, because the club couldn't count on these players.
Obviously the advantage is that players will start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future match.
But this is a long-term advantage, with a certain degree of indeterminacy, because the team could be eliminated suddenly and apart from that, with this action the players complete a penalty match and move on to the second round of cards, in which the suspension due to the accumulation of cards occurs with one less than in the first round.
So, climbing the stairs, it is not so clear that this is an advantage.
Ultimately, these actions are not contrary to the sporting spirit, of which strategic decisions are still part that promote the maximum benefit of what the rules allow.
In our case, the players did not act to avoid the application of the sanction (this would indeed be a clear case of fraud of the law),m otherwise they chose rather the moment in which they submitted to it.
They made a strategic decision without overriding the penalty or escaping it.
Although the line between genius and law fraud is wide, on this occasion I think we have had a clear case of genius.
The controversy, it seems to me, arises because of two factors: because there have been two self-expulsions and because of the way in which the director conveys them to provoke them.
The harm caused to the principles of sport by these actions is not as ethical as aesthetic.
