Pakistan's nuclear program raises major concerns in the United States
“Islamabad is producing nuclear weapons at a faster rate than any other country.”
Wikileaks leaks confirm the connection between the Taliban and Pakistan.
The content of the correspondence between the U.S. Embassy in Pakistan and the U.S. State Department filtered through the Wikileaks portal confirms the enormous concerns caused by the Pakistani nuclear program in Washington.
Apart from the enlightening and tasty details they offer on the content of the conversations and thoughts of North American diplomatic representatives accredited in Islamabad, the documents reveal the fact that cooperation between the two countries in the field of atomic security, instead of increasing, "decreases" and that the other unstable Asian country produces nuclear weapons "more than a rythm".
The peculiarity of Pakistan's nuclear program - the fact that weapons are not assembled, but are stored in components to make their destruction difficult in the event of an attack - is one of the main concerns in Washington.
The ambassador to Pakistan, Anne W. Patterson, said in a report before the visit of former National Security Advisor James Jones: “The proximity of some of the territory’s nuclear facilities under attack by the Taliban, the dispersal of nuclear materials with short noise and the vulnerability of the transport of atomic materials.”
The large number of people involved in nuclear arsenals and missile programs is seen, not only by the United States, but also by Russia, as proliferating and a reason to maintain guard.
"Pakistan has had to hire personnel with strict religious beliefs to protect nuclear facilities; given the decline in educational and cultural levels, extremist organizations have more opportunities to recruit people who work in nuclear or missile programs," said expert Yuri Korolev, from the U.S. Department of Foreign Affairs.
The new documentation leaked by the Julian Assange portal is the ever-increasing cooperation between the United States and Pakistan in the field of nuclear proliferation and Pakistan’s high degree of nuclear weapons production.
An embassy dispatch in May, which described the communication with Pakistan as “frustrating,” said: “Transparency is often non-existent; offers of assistance remain unanswered or are eliminated.”
In another message, Peter Lavoy, a National Intelligence official for South Asia, notes that “despite the economic catastrophe, Pakistan is producing nuclear weapons at a faster rate than any other country in the world.”
Ambassador Patterson also asked Washington, during a visit by Army Chief General Ashfaq Kayani, to make it "very clear" to the official that "Pakistan's army must end its tacit support for terrorist groups."
