Interpol issues a red alert to track movements and locate Assange.
All aspects of Wikileaks and its founder, Julian Assange, form a complicated maze where it is difficult to be certain of the facts.
Yesterday, Interpol issued a “red alert” to “locate and track the movements” of Assange.
However, this is not a traditional arrest warrant.
In addition, this is not new, otherwise it dates from November 20.
And it has nothing to do with the latest leak of more than a quarter of a million U.S. diplomatic documents but with the accusations of sexual abuse that the Australian faces in Sweden.
In addition, Wikileaks’s creative lawyer, Mark Stephens, says that “the police know where and how to contact Mr. Assange.”
The 20th international police force based in Lyon (France) issued the order at the request of Sweden, but it did not make it public until yesterday, after receiving permission from the authorities of that country.
For example, the 188 countries of Interpol were instructed to identify or locate Assange "to obtain his provisional arrest and extradition".
Although Interpol cannot give the arrest order of an individual affected by a red alert, many of the member countries, according to the organization's explanations, consider the red notice call a free path for arrest -- which the national police force must carry out -- where they think they have a bilateral agreement on extradition, as well as an extradition case.
The movement outraged Assange’s lawyers, who yesterday published a letter denouncing the fact that the founder of Wikileaks, 39, was willing to answer questions from the Swedish authorities via videoconference.
They also recall that Assange applied for and obtained permission to leave Sweden from the prosecutor of his case, which is compared to the famous Lavrentiy Pavlovich Beria, head of Stalin's security.
“This appears to be a hunt, not a legal persecution,” the letter said.
As the world searches for him – and in Australia his mother defends his son’s innocence – Assange continues to find himself in an unknown place, but he does not remain silent.
On Monday, he gave an indeterminate interview to the director of Time magazine via Skype, a conversation in which he called for the resignation of U.S. Secretary of State Hillary Clinton.
“If it can be shown that she was responsible for giving orders to American graduates who are spying on the UN in violation of international treaties that the United States has signed, she should resign,” he said.
His opinion was insulted yesterday by White House press secretary Robert Gibbs, who called the resignation request "ridiculous and absurd."
"I'm not at all sure why the opinion of a guy with a web page should interest us," he told CNN.
Obama himself has tasked a senior anti-terrorism official, Russell Travers, to prevent further leaks.
President Barack Obama’s attempt to reduce Assange’s importance contrasts with the views that conservative politicians and commentators are proclaiming these days.
Peter King, the congressman who will chair the National Security Committee in the Lower House from January, has asked the State Department to consider including Wikileaks in the list of terrorist organizations “to confiscate its funds and prosecute anyone who provides contributions or assistance to them.”
Even further went Tom Flanagan, an adviser to Canadian President Stephen Harper, who had to return on his statements after saying that Assange would have to be "murdered".
"Obama should turn it into a target and use an unmanned plane or something like that."
One person who did not apologize was Mike Huckabee, Baptist minister, former governor of Arkansas and possible presidential candidate.
"He who is in the government that leaked the information is guilty of treason and anything that is not an execution would be too kind a punishment," he told Fox.
