The European Union changes the rules for obtaining a visa
Individuals must go to the Visa Applicants Service Centers before their interview in the Consular Section; the cost of waiting time will be reduced.
As of January 10, 2011, the visa processing procedure at the U.S. Embassy and Consulates will change.
With the new procedure, the majority of applicants will be required to report to the Visa Applicant Service Centres (ASCs) prior to their interview in the Consular Section.
CSA staff will take biometric information from the applicant, which will be reviewed by the Consular Section prior to the interview.
The new procedure will have some benefits for applicants, including the following:
The total cost to process the visa will be lower, it will no longer be necessary to make a payment to get an appointment, another payment for the visa processing and another for the mail service to deliver the document.
The applicant will make a single payment covering all three services.
The current tariff will remain the same: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visas with demand (this includes visas for temporary workers) and $390 for merchant and investor visas.
Individuals wishing to renew their visa will not be required to present themselves for an interview with the Consular Representative, they will only present themselves at the nearest CSA where they will present the documents and take their fingerprints.
Due to the fact that the biometric information will be taken from the CSA, applicants who wish a second appointment to be interviewed in the Consular Section will remain there for less time than before.
Similarly, visa applicants at the Consulates of Ciudad Ju<0xC3><0xA1>rez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the $26 extra service fee.
For more information on the new visa application procedure, visit the following page http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
