A Global Plan to Renovate Lighting
The United Nations has proposed in Cancun a plan to renovate domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in 100 countries to achieve a greenhouse gas (GHG) reduction that is nearly one-third of the additional reduction needed to stabilize the global climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan is in line with the major concrete projects that the United Nations hopes to have adopted in Cancun to compensate for the lack of binding reduction commitments by the industrialized countries.
According to the plan tabled yesterday, if the incandescent bulbs that still monopolize 50 to 70% of the market were replaced by fluo-compact bulbs or, better yet, by light-emitting diode bulbs (DEL or "LED" in English), the bulk of the 1.8 billion tons (Gt) of GHG emitted would be human.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This is the equivalent of 70% of the global fleet’s emissions.
In Copenhagen last year, major emitting countries, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed to voluntary reduction plans that are expected to increase global GHG emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But it will be necessary to subtract another 5 Gt from this balance sheet in order to stabilise the climate increase to 2 degrees Celsius by 2020 in order to prevent it from becoming out of control.
In incandescent bulbs, 95% of the energy is dissipated in the form of heat and the rest, or 5%, is produced by light.
With fluo-compact bulbs, the energy consumption is reduced by 75% and with the new LED bulbs, this energy requirement is reduced twice more.
Fluocompact bulbs last an average of 6,000 to 10,000 hours.
The new LED bulbs, such as those launched by the manufacturer Philips this week - the company also participated in the UN study - have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent bulb, giving an idea of the possible economy with a country-wide replacement plan that applies.
These brand new bulbs can also work with rheostats in addition to emitting very little heat.
And they don't contain any mercury.
A number of experts have made reservations about compact fluorescent bulbs as they contain mercury and should be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, unless manufacturers put in place guidelines.
But, the report says, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not the fluo-compact bulb, but rather coal-fired thermal power plants, which emit a lot of mercury to produce wasted electricity in incandescent bulbs.
In the United States alone, these plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury per year.
The report details the gains that each country would make through this international programme.
For example, Indonesia would save one billion dollars a year in electricity purchases and eight million tons of CO2, the equivalent of 3.5 thermal power plants whose construction would cost it 2.5 billion.
