Avenger Hackers and Spies in Diligence
The WikiLeaks case has a double value.
On the one hand, it turns out to be an apparent scandal, a scandal that only appears as a scandal in the face of the hypocrisy that governs relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it announces profound changes at the international level, and foreshadows a future dominated by regression.
But let's proceed by order.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation that every file made up of a secret service (of any nation) is made up exclusively of press cuts.
The "extraordinary" American revelations about Berlusconi's sexual habits only report what for months could be read in any newspaper (except those Berlusconi owns), and Gaddafi's sinisterly caricatured profile was long overdue for cabaret artists.
The rule that secret files should be composed only of news already known is essential to the dynamics of the secret services, and not only in this century.
If you go to a bookstore dedicated to esoteric publications, you will see that each book repeats (on the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Ch<0xC3><0xA2>teau, the Templars or the Rose-Cross) exactly what was already written in the previous books.
And this is not only because the author of occult texts does not like to do unpublished research (nor knows where to look for news about the non-existent), but because those who devote themselves to occultism believe only what they already know, and who reconfirms what they had already learned.
It is the mechanism of success of Dan Brown.
Same goes for the secret files.
The informant is lazy, and lazy (or of limited mind) the head of the secret services (otherwise he could be, I know, the editor of Libération), who retain as true only what he recognizes.
The top secret information about Berlusconi that the U.S. Embassy in Rome sent to the State Department was the same as Newsweek published the week before.
So why did the revelations on these files make so much noise?
On the one hand, they say what every cultivated person already knows, namely that the embassies, at least since the end of the Second World War, and since the heads of state can call or take a plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of a few small exercises of representation, have become centers.
Any viewer of investigative films knows this very well, and it is only through hypocrisy that one pretends to ignore it.
However, repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy, and serves to put American diplomacy in a bad light.
Secondly, the idea that any hacker could capture the most secretive secrets of the world’s most powerful country is a not-too-negligible blow to the prestige of the State Department.
So the scandal does not put so much the victims in crisis as the "strangers".
But let’s come to the profound nature of what happened.
Once upon a time, in Orwell's time, one could conceive of all power as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
Orwellian prophecy had been fully proven since, being able to control every movement through the telephone, every transaction made, the hotel visited, the highway taken, and so on, the citizen became the total victim of the eye of power.
But when it is shown, as it is now, that even the crypts of the secrets of power cannot escape the control of a hacker, the control relationship ceases to be unidirectional and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker – elected as the citizen’s avenger – can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power that no longer has the power to keep its own secrets hold?
It is true, Georg Simmel has already said, that a real secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true, that knowing everything about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is indeed an empty secret, because it is in the public domain; but to reveal, as WikiLeaks has done, that all the secrets of Hillary Clinton are empty secrets to her.
WikiLeaks has done no harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but it has done too much to Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this injury inflicted on a very powerful power?
It is obvious that in the future, states will no longer be able to put online any reserved information - this would mean publishing it on a poster glued to the corner of the street.
But it is just as obvious that with current technologies, it is futile to hope to be able to maintain confidential reports over the phone.
Nothing is easier than to find out if and when a head of state flew and contacted one of his colleagues.
How can private and reserved relationships be maintained in the future?
I know that, for the moment, my prediction is science fiction and is therefore romantic, but I am obliged to imagine government agents who move discreetly in due diligence on uncontrollable routes, carrying only messages learned by heart or, at the most, hiding the rare information in writing.
The information will be kept in one copy in locked drawers: deep down, the Watergate spying attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
I had the opportunity to write that the technology is now advancing in crab, that is, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communications, the Internet restored a wired telegraph (telephones).
The (analog) videotapes had allowed film researchers to explore a film step by step, going back and forth and discovering all the secrets of editing, while now the (digital) CDs only allow you to jump from chapter to chapter, that is, by macroportions.
With high-speed trains, we go from Rome to Milan in three hours, while by plane, and the trips it includes, it takes three and a half hours.
It is therefore not surprising that the policy and communication techniques come back to horse-drawn cars.
One last observation.
In the past, the press was trying to understand what was going on inside the embassies.
Now, it is the embassies that are asking for confidential information from the press.
