Again, there is no rule and everyone chooses their calculation method.
Some, like France, consider that 1<0xE2><0x82><0xAC> borrowed is equivalent to 1<0xE2><0x82><0xAC> given.
Obviously, this is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often projects related to the mitigation of emissions that are based on more efficient technologies), it is fallacious to present a euro that will be recovered as equivalent to a euro that is given... At most, the loan's value should only be counted as the amount of its commitments.
But France only has to do with such a reasoning: it "respects" its commitment of 420 million euros by making 91.5% loans (389.8 million euros) and 8.5% donations (36.1 million euros) - see the EU document to check for yourself.
It is the only country in the Union to use the loan so massively.
Germany requires 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (in others) meet their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the vast majority of the European Union puts <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>1 to meet its commitment, France puts only 10 cents and considers that the effort is comparable.
Nice pass-through tour!
In short, in its fast start financing, France is operating a double scam: on the one hand on the evolution of the action over time and on the other hand on the reality of the financial effort.
By spending only <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>36.1 million, she comes to believe that she is spending <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>420 million "new and additional" in line with her promises.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that Bercy carried out the arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would other Member States continue to give if it is enough to lend?) and in the negotiations since developing countries are not completely deceived...
The early funding chapter is only a small, relatively short-term issue compared to all the climate discussions.
But it could be one more grain of sand in the huge machine that is the UNFCCC.
Let us hope that this will not be the case.
In any case, it is essential to learn from this first year of early funding.
First, France could announce a change in its accounting for the years 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its commitments and fairness with the other countries of the European Union.
But most importantly, France could push forward the discussions on the issues of long-term financing (another crucial chapter currently discussed): the question of "additionality" or the way in which loans are accounted for will not be avoided.
France could change its position to become as progressive on these issues as it is on others.
The hope is therefore based on the new Minister of the Environment, Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement about France’s fast start and its vision of “additionality” and the use of loans would naturally increase the level of international confidence needed to move forward in the discussions.
Alert to pesticides ingested by children
A 10-year-old child ingests 81 different chemicals in one day, according to a study published Wednesday by the Générations Futures (formerly the Movement for the Rights and Respect of Future Generations) association.
The association, which warns that its results "have no significant statistical value in view of the low number of samples analyzed, but are illustrative of the problem", bought between July and September the foods generally consumed in four meals and an encadas in a day by a child of about ten years, in the supermarkets of Paris and Paris.
These standard meals, including official recommendations - five fresh fruits and vegetables, three dairy products and 1.5 liters of water per day - as well as sweets, have been examined by laboratories looking for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The balance sheet is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, 42 of which are classified as possible or probable carcinogens and five substances classified as certain carcinogens, as well as 37 substances likely to act as endocrine disruptors (PEs), according to studies by several institutions such as the International Cancer Research Centre.
"Although, in almost all cases, the legal limits for each individual chemical substance taken are not exceeded, our survey clearly shows that the reality of consumer exposure to potentially carcinogenic and/or PE contaminants is of concern," notes the association.
For breakfast, butter and milk tea alone contain more than a dozen possible carcinogenic residues and three proven to be certain carcinogens, as well as nearly twenty residues likely to disrupt the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, planned as a snack by the study, has traces of six chemical substances, one of which is banned in France.
The same goes for Kenya’s green beans, included in the lunch, on which the study found traces of a powerful insecticide banned in the EU.
In addition, chopped steak, canned tuna, and even breadstick and chewing gum were loaded with pesticides and other chemicals.
In the tap water the analyses revealed the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
For dinner, salmon steak was the most “rich” with 34 chemical residues detected and even the examination of the plastic plate used to heat the microwave meal was not exempt.
The final risk to the consumer of this “contaminant cocktail” is “probably underestimated,” according to the study.
The Alliance Europe Ecologie-Les Verts (EE-LV), for its part, has proposed "in the face of the urgency of the situation" to introduce a moratorium on the use of pesticides, in order to stop "the increase of civilization diseases".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) reported the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruits and vegetables consumed in Europe, including 76 in cereals.
